[[File:Bagawat.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The El Bagawat Christian cemetery at Kharga Oasis]]
'''El Bagawat''', is an ancient Christian cemetery, one of the oldest in the world, which functioned at the [[Kharga Oasis]] in southern-central [[Egypt]] from the 3rd to the 7th century AD. It is one of the earliest and best preserved Christian cemeteries from the ancient world.

==Location==
The Necropolis of El Bagawat is located in the [[Western Desert (Egypt)|Western Desert]] in Kharga Oasis. This is one of the largest oases in Egypt and is 34 m below sea level.{{sfn|Stoppato|2003|p=135}}

==History==
The El Bagawat cemetery is reported to be pre-historic<ref name=Necro/> and is one of the oldest Christian cemeteries in Egypt.{{sfn|Richardson|2003|p=544}}<ref name=Necro/> Before Christianity was introduced into Egypt, it was a burial ground used by the non-Christians and later years by the Christians. The chapels here are said to belong to both the eras.{{sfn|Meinardus|1977|p=483}} Coptic frescoes of the 3rd to the 7th century are found on the walls.{{sfn|Gianfagna|2013|p=25}} There are 263 funerary chapels of which the Chapel of Exodus (5th or 6th century) and Chapel of Peace (of mid 4th century) have frescoes.{{sfn|Wire|Chaney|2004|p=234}}

==Features==
The El Bagawat cemetery has a very large number of tombs in the form of chapel domes.<ref name=Necro/>{{sfn|Ham|2010|p=176}} They are built of mud bricks. The tombs have etchings of biblical stories,<ref name=Necro>{{cite book|title=Egitto. 7000 Anni Di Storia. Ediz. Inglese|url=
https://books.google.com/books?id=_L7jmg_YUyoC&pg=PA247
|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Casa Editrice Bonechi|isbn=978-88-476-1867-1|pages=247–}}</ref>
and also of saints and “personifications of virtues”.<ref name=Necro/>{{sfn|Ham|2010|p=176}}

In the Exodus Chapel, there is depiction of [[martyrdom]] of [[Isiah]];<ref name=Adam>{{cite book|title=Coptic Church Review|pages=119,125|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u2EnAQAAMAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Coptic Church Review.}}</ref> and also of Tekla postured with raised hands, in front of fire being doused by rain. In the Chapel of Peace, the illustrative fresco is of Thekla and Paul.{{sfn|Wire|Chaney|2004|p=234}}

There are paintings in the cemetery which show the [[ark of Noah]] in the form of an "Egyptian barque". Also notable are carved representations of [[Old Testament]] scriptures, including [[Adam and Eve]], [[Daniel in the lion's den]], the sacrifice of [[Abraham]], and Jonah swallowed by a fish.<ref name=Adam/>

